>
  <main id="main"><header class="page-hero page-hero--portrait"><div class="container"><div class="breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">Home</a> / <a href="host-institutions.html">Host Institutions</a> / Appointment Model</div><span class="kicker">Appointment model</span><h1>From institutional need to accountable contribution</h1><p>A fellowship appointment joins a selected Fellow, a humanity-scale mission, a qualified host, and a defined project or role.</p></div></header><nav class="anchor-nav anchor-nav--bar" aria-label="On this page"><div class="container"><a href="#overview"><span>01</span>Overview</a><a href="#process"><span>02</span>How it works</a><a href="#focus"><span>03</span>Areas of focus</a><a href="#principles"><span>04</span>Principles</a><a href="#next"><span>05</span>Next steps</a></div></nav><section class="section profile-opening" id="overview"><div class="container profile-grid"><div class="prose"><span class="eyebrow">For Host Institutions</span><h2>A shared structure for accountable contribution</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>The appointment model aligns four elements: a selected Fellow, a humanity-scale mission, a qualified host, and a defined contribution.</p><p>Clarity across those elements prevents fellowship from becoming an honorary label on one side or an unsupported work request on the other.</p><p>The Fellow establishes the point of entry; the contribution defines what should remain after the immediate work is complete.</p></div><aside class="profile-emblem"><span>Perspective</span><strong>01</strong><p>The Fellow establishes the point of entry; the contribution defines what should remain after the immediate work is complete.</p></aside></div></section><section class="section section--blue" id="process"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">From intent to practice</span><h2>Building a strong host relationship</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Good appointments begin before a Fellow arrives. Hosts clarify the work, establish support, and agree on what responsible completion looks like.</p></div><div class="process-path"><article class="step"><h3>Propose</h3><p>Describe the mission, institutional need, likely work, intended benefit, and responsible owner. Here, attend to the fellow: Brings relevant capability, character, readiness, and commitment to the Code of Service.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Qualify</h3><p>Confirm organizational standing, supervision, resources, role clarity, and alignment with Society standards. Here, attend to the mission: Provides the public-interest reason for the appointment and the larger outcome it seeks to advance.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Match and shape</h3><p>Align the opportunity with a Fellow&#x27;s capabilities and turn it into a realistic appointment plan. Here, attend to the host: Provides institutional setting, supervision, context, access, and responsibility for the opportunity.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Support and close</h3><p>Provide feedback throughout the work, review outcomes, and capture lessons at completion. Here, attend to the contribution: Defines the work, outputs, boundaries, learning, and intended benefit in practical terms.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section section--mist" id="focus"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">The host relationship</span><h2>What a consequential host setting must provide</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>The appointment model aligns four elements: a selected Fellow, a humanity-scale mission, a qualified host, and a defined contribution.</p></div><div class="profile-focus"><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="compass" /><div><span class="item-index">01</span><h3>The Fellow</h3><p>Brings relevant capability, character, readiness, and commitment to the Code of Service.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="institution" /><div><span class="item-index">02</span><h3>The mission</h3><p>Provides the public-interest reason for the appointment and the larger outcome it seeks to advance.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="lightbulb-o" /><div><span class="item-index">03</span><h3>The host</h3><p>Provides institutional setting, supervision, context, access, and responsibility for the opportunity.</p></div></article><article class="focus-item"><LegacyIcon name="handshake-o" /><div><span class="item-index">04</span><h3>The contribution</h3><p>Defines the work, outputs, boundaries, learning, and intended benefit in practical terms.</p></div></article></div></div></section><section class="section section--navy" id="principles"><div class="container narrative-standard"><div><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Conditions for trust</span><h2>The responsibilities of a qualified host</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Responsible hosting requires a real need, capable supervision, and mutual clarity from the outset.</p></div></div><div class="principle-list"><article class="principle-row"><span>01</span><div><h3>A credible need</h3><p>The opportunity should respond to real institutional or public-interest work rather than create an ornamental role.</p></div></article><article class="principle-row"><span>02</span><div><h3>Responsible support</h3><p>A Fellow needs a designated supervisor, appropriate access, timely feedback, and a safe working setting.</p></div></article><article class="principle-row"><span>03</span><div><h3>Mutual value</h3><p>The appointment should respect the Fellow&#x27;s capabilities while producing useful value for the mission and institution.</p></div></article></div></div></section><section class="section close-quote" id="next"><div class="container"><blockquote>“The Fellow establishes the point of entry; the contribution defines what should remain after the immediate work is complete.”</blockquote><div><div><h2>Shape an opportunity the Society can assess</h2><p>Begin with the fellow, then define a contribution your capabilities or institution can support.</p></div><div class="actions"><a class="button button--gold" href="submit-opportunity.html">Submit an opportunity</a><a class="button button--outline" href="become-a-host.html">Become a Host</a></div></div><aside class="related-panel"><span class="eyebrow">Continue exploring</span><h3>Related pathways</h3><ul class="related-list"><li><a href="host-institutions.html">Host overview</a></li><li><a href="host-standards.html">Host standards</a></li><li><a href="appointment-model.html">Appointment model</a></li></ul></aside></div></section></main>

